{"name":"Navarre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Jacques, Anatole, Angelle, Camille, Marcelle.","French: habitational name from Navarre (see   Navarra  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Navarra","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Sal, Edgardo, Guido, Santo, Vito, Angelo, Annamarie, Antonio, Benedicto, Camillo, Dante, Emilio, Fausto, Gaetano, Giuseppe, Mario, Romulo, Sergio.  Spanish Agustin, Herlinda, Manuel, Solita.","Spanish, Portuguese, Italian, and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name from Navarre (Castilian <i>Navarra</i>, Basque <i>Nafarroa</i>, French <i>Navarre</i>), a largely Basque-speaking region now divided between Spain and France, but in the Middle Ages an independent Basque kingdom. The name of the region derives from Basque <i>naba</i> ‘plain next to mountains’. Compare   Navarre  ."]}]},{"name":"Adela","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Adele  , especially popular in the late 19th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Adella","meanings":["form of   Adele  , especially popular in the late 19th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lithuise Adela de Navarre was born in 1071, in Centre, France. She married Herve de Léon I before 1090, in Brittany, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1118, in Bray-sur-Seine, Provins, Seine-et-Marne, France, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1071–1118":"1071–1118","1070–1128":"1070–1128","1087–1157":"1087–1157","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1094–1157":"1094–1157","1112–1185":"1112–1185","1118":"1118","before 1090":"enne 1090","1090":"1090","1128":"1128","1157":"1157","1112":"1112","1087":"1087","1185":"1185","about 1087":"umbes 1087","1094":"1094","1071":"1071","1070":"1070","Centre, France":"Centre, Prantsusmaa","Saint-Pol-de-Léon, Bretagne, France":"Saint-Pol-de-Léon, Breta